The subject of a dependent's behaviour is continued, bnt in a different veinÍ¾ this time in a letter which has, in part at least, close relations to the circumstances of Lollius. It is not a needy rnau making np to a patron for a dinner and for the benefit of his relations (Ep. 17. ari, but a man born in good position. The Epistle speaks (vv. 60-64) of his fatherâs estate, and he is probably the Lollius of Ep. a, aud theson of the Lollius who was consul in ac. ar (Ep. ao. 28). He is thought of as entering the friendship not of some merely rich patron, bnt of a âpotens amicus,' a rnan high in the political world, with secreta of importance which his protlgl must respect and keep (vv. 37, 38 and 68-70). The Epistle, however, is not free from difficulties. The dangers against which Lollius iswamed in vv. 21-36 and 72-75 seem ill suited to the kind of character pre- sumed in the rest of the poemÍ¾ and, taking the Epistle as a whole, and supposing that Lollius had really attached himself to some one of high position in the Court circle, it is not easy to believe that its immediate publication can have been agreeÎ able either to patron or protlgl. This last supposition, however, is not necessary. The conditions of the case are satisfied if Lollius,a young literary friend of the poet. was contemplating the acceptance of such an office as that which Augustus himself offered to Horace, or that which Celsus holds in Ep. 8Í¾ and if Horace- wrote to him, perhaps at his request, sketching the duties and dangers of a private secretary iu a great house. Part of the lecture may have been evidently playful, and the issue of the Epistle may have been that Lollius declined the office.

lt is to be noticed that any disrespect to Lollius is out of the question, supposing him to be the person we imagine. lt seems also that the Epistle was written in n. c. ao (see on v. 56 and introd. to the Epistlcs, p. aoy), and published therefore within a few months.
